                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d679">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 Armament Control/64: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>U. S. S. “<hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >Houston</hi>”</placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1935-10-05">October 5, 1935</date>.<lb/>[Received 3:20
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Approve statement to accompany proclamation covering Section 1 of Neutrality Act.
                    I am very strongly of belief that other proclamation relating to passenger
                    travel under Section 6 should also be issued. The fact that Ethiopia has no
                    ships is not controlling, because that argument might apply to munition
                    shipments as well. The intent of the Act is to prevent aid to either belligerent
                    and American passenger travel on Italian ships gives aid not only financially
                    but also by making access to Italy more easy for Americans seeking commercial
                    advantages. I strongly urge that the record of strict adherence to spirit of the
                    Act be maintained.</p>
                <closer>[File copy not signed.]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
